const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What BlueStar appliances do you repair in Los Angeles?",
    a: "All current BlueStar US categories. Ranges across the open-burner lineup (RNB-series 30 / 36 / 48 / 60-inch professional ranges, Platinum series BSP variants with higher-spec components, Heritage Classic configurations), rangetops (RCS-series 30 / 36 / 48-inch), wall ovens (BSWO standard and Platinum variants), cooktops, range hoods (matching the range collections), plus the newer refrigerator and dishwasher lineup BlueStar has added to round out the kitchen suite. The open-burner ranges are the dominant service category in our LA mix — they're the brand's signature product and what most BlueStar owners specified the brand for. Within BlueStar's actual US lineup we service the full range, 2010-onward manufacture dates dominant."
  },
  {
    q: "My BlueStar burner keeps clicking — what's wrong?",
    a: "Continuous clicking after the burner lights (or clicking with no spark at all) is one of the most common BlueStar service calls we run, and the diagnosis is usually one of two things. (1) <strong>Spark module failure on the simmer burner</strong>. The 2016-2021 RNB-series cohort develops a consistent simmer-burner spark module pattern around year 4-6 — the module sticks in continuous-spark mode after the burner has already lit, producing the persistent clicking sound. Replacement runs $245-$385, typically same-day when we stock the common RNB spark modules on the truck. (2) <strong>Ceramic igniter cracked or fouled</strong>. LA coastal kitchens (Santa Monica, Venice, Manhattan Beach, Pacific Palisades) see this faster than inland — the combination of grease vapor and marine-layer moisture degrades the ceramic faster than dry inland air does. Symptoms: clicking without ignition, or clicking that only stops after the burner lights manually with a match. Replacement $165-$265 per igniter. We diagnose which on-site — sometimes both fail together on heavily-used burners and we replace as a paired service. Pre-2016 RNB units occasionally show gas valve issues rather than spark hardware — diagnostic separates which on the visit."
  },
  {
    q: "How much does BlueStar range repair cost in LA?",
    a: "Diagnostic is $89, applied toward the repair when you approve the work. Common BlueStar range repairs: ceramic igniter $165-$265 per burner; spark module $245-$385; surface burner cap and ring $80-$145; gas valve assembly $345-$525; oven igniter $165-$265; oven thermostat $245-$385; convection fan motor on RNB convection units $325-$485 (the convection fan is dedicated to the bake / broil cavity); infrared broiler element $385-$580 (BlueStar's infrared broiler element is heavier-duty than standard electric broilers and reflects in parts cost); oven door hinge $345-$525; door glass $385-$680; main control board $345-$525 (BlueStar's control electronics are simpler than Wolf or Thermador — fewer touch-control assemblies, more straightforward to replace). Parts ship directly from Prizer-Painter (BlueStar's parent — independent, not in the BSH or GE Appliances network), typical 3-7 day lead time, common wear parts for the RNB / RCS series on the truck for same-day completion. The independent parts supply is one of BlueStar's service advantages — we don't navigate authorized-service-only gates that complicate other luxury brands."
  },
  {
    q: "Is it worth repairing a BlueStar range?",
    a: "Almost always, and the math is favorable. BlueStar ranges are built to last 20-25 years with normal use — cast iron grates, brass burner valves, all-stainless construction, mechanical simplicity (fewer electronics than competing luxury ranges). The components that wear are predictable: spark modules at year 4-6 ($245-$385), ceramic igniters at year 5-8 in coastal LA addresses or year 7-10 inland ($165-$265 per zone), oven thermostat year 6-9 ($245-$385), convection fan motor year 8-12 ($325-$485). Replacement-unit pricing: RNB 30-inch starts around $5,500, RNB 36-inch around $7,500, RNB 48-inch professional around $10,500, Platinum BSP variants run $12,000-$15,000. Against those numbers, a $400-$600 repair on a 15-year-old BlueStar is a no-brainer — the brass valves and cast iron grates have another decade in them, and the repair recovers another 5-10 years of service life. The exception: severe structural damage from a household incident, or compressor failure on the newer BlueStar refrigerator line which carries replacement-cost math closer to the mass-market refrigerator category."
  },
  {
    q: "Can you match my custom-color BlueStar if a panel needs replacement?",
    a: "Sometimes — and this is one of BlueStar's most distinctive service realities worth understanding. BlueStar offers 190+ standard color options plus custom RAL colors on order, which means the front panel finish on your range may have been a specific RAL code chosen during the original spec. <strong>If your color is still in BlueStar's current catalog</strong>, panel replacement is a coordination job through Prizer-Painter: identify the exact RAL code from the original spec sheet (sometimes printed on a sticker inside the lower front panel; sometimes only available from the dealer who originally sold the unit), order through Prizer-Painter, 14-28 day lead. Cost varies by panel size: 30-inch panels $385-$580, 36-inch $485-$780, 48-inch $680-$1,100. <strong>If your color was a limited-run or custom RAL that's been discontinued</strong>, panel replacement may not be possible — Prizer-Painter doesn't always carry archived custom finishes. In that case repair (rather than replacement) is the only path to keep the kitchen aesthetic intact, which is part of why we tell BlueStar owners with custom colors that the math always favors repair over a full unit swap. We coordinate the panel order through Prizer-Painter directly if it's available."
  },
  {
    q: "How does BlueStar compare to Wolf for repair costs?",
    a: "Honest comparison from working on both regularly: BlueStar repair costs run roughly 30-50% lower than Wolf for equivalent components, mostly because of three differences. First, <strong>BlueStar uses simpler control electronics</strong> — fewer touch-control assemblies, fewer integrated electronic modules, more mechanical / electromechanical components that are cheaper to replace. Second, <strong>Prizer-Painter direct parts supply</strong> is independent of the major-brand distribution networks that Wolf (Sub-Zero Group), Thermador (BSH), Viking (Middleby) all route through. BlueStar parts ship directly from the manufacturer with typical 3-7 day lead, no authorized-service-only gating, no per-part premium pricing tier. Third, <strong>open-burner architecture is mechanically simpler</strong> than Wolf's dual-stacked sealed burners — fewer parts per burner, more straightforward diagnostic, lower per-zone repair cost. Practical numbers: ceramic igniter replacement on BlueStar $165-$265, comparable Wolf zone-igniter service $245-$385. Oven thermostat: BlueStar $245-$385, Wolf $345-$525. Convection fan motor: BlueStar $325-$485, Wolf $485-$680. The longevity is similar between the two brands; the service-economics gap is structural to how each brand handles parts distribution."
  },
  {
    q: "Where can I find the official BlueStar manual or warranty information?",
    a: `Our technicians work independently of BlueStar's factory service network — we're often faster and available same-day in Southern California.`
  }
