<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">BlueStar is the serious home cook's range — open commercial burners, 25,000 BTU, 190+ color options — and we see them in kitchens where the owner specifically wanted what Wolf isn't.</h2>

    <p>BlueStar is manufactured by Prizer-Painter Stove Works in Reading, Pennsylvania. Prizer-Painter has been making cooking equipment since 1880; the BlueStar consumer brand launched in 2002 to bring restaurant-style open-burner architecture into residential kitchens. The brand is family-owned, American-made, and notably independent — not part of the BSH conglomerate (Bosch / Thermador / Gaggenau), not part of GE Appliances (Monogram / Café / Profile), not part of Sub-Zero Group (Sub-Zero / Wolf / Cove), not part of Middleby (Viking / Lynx / AGA). In our 5-county SoCal service area, BlueStar shows up in a specific owner profile: serious home cooks in Beverly Hills, Pasadena, and Silver Lake who chose BlueStar specifically because Wolf felt too corporate, plus design-forward kitchens in West Hollywood and Manhattan Beach where the 190+ color options (and the custom RAL color program) made BlueStar the only viable choice.</p>

    <p>Three BlueStar-specific realities shape every service call we run. First, <strong>open-burner architecture is fundamentally different from sealed-burner ranges</strong> (Wolf, Thermador, Viking, Bertazzoni all use sealed burners). The burner cap, burner ring, igniter, and spark module are exposed and accessible rather than enclosed beneath a sealed gas-tight surface. Service implication: faster diagnostics, lower parts costs per zone, more straightforward repairs. The flip side is that grease and food debris fall directly onto the burner hardware in normal use — the open architecture trades cleaning complexity for service complexity, deliberately. Second, <strong>Prizer-Painter direct parts supply</strong> means BlueStar parts ship from the Reading PA factory through Prizer-Painter's own distribution network, 3-7 day typical lead time, with no authorized-service-only gating. We don't navigate the major-brand distribution chains that complicate Wolf, Thermador, or Miele service. Third, <strong>190+ color options including custom RAL</strong> is a service consideration competitors don't even think about — when a panel needs replacement, color matching is a coordination job through Prizer-Painter direct, and on discontinued custom colors the answer can be "repair is the only path."</p>

    <p>This page covers BlueStar repair across the full US lineup — ranges (the bulk of our work), rangetops, wall ovens, cooktops, infrared broilers, range hoods. BlueStar's newer refrigerator and dishwasher additions get lighter coverage because LA service volume is still modest on those categories. Every BlueStar service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM Prizer-Painter parts, and an honest written quote before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 RANGES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, BlueStar range repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">RNB open-burner, RCS rangetop, Platinum BSP — the open-burner service tree.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Ranges and rangetops are the bulk of our BlueStar service work in LA. RNB-series open-burner professional ranges (30, 36, 48, and 60-inch widths) dominate the service mix; RCS rangetops fill the cooktop-without-oven configuration; Platinum BSP variants run higher-spec components but share most of the service tree with standard RNB.</p>

    <div class="callout-box">
      <h3>2016-2021 RNB simmer burner spark module pattern (most common BlueStar service call in LA)</h3>
      <p>The RNB366BV2 and surrounding RNB-series production years between roughly 2016 and 2021 develop a consistent simmer burner spark module failure around year 4 to 6. Symptoms: continuous clicking from the simmer burner even after it has lit normally, sometimes clicking when no burner is in use (module stuck in continuous-spark mode), occasionally the affected zone failing to spark at all once the module fully fails. Module replacement is the fix — single component, $245-$385 with labor. <strong>Same-day when we stock the common RNB spark modules on the truck</strong>, which we do for the dominant 36-inch and 48-inch configurations. Worth pairing with a ceramic igniter inspection at the same visit; igniters in coastal LA addresses degrade on a similar timeline and matched-cohort service is more efficient than a return visit.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Beyond the simmer burner spark module pattern, BlueStar range service tree covers a predictable set of items by year-window:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 3-5:</strong> Surface burner cap and ring wear (cosmetic / function, $80-$145 per zone — open-burner architecture means these are accessible items), ceramic igniter on coastal-LA addresses ($165-$265 per zone, accelerated by marine-layer humidity plus grease).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 4-6:</strong> Simmer burner spark module (above on RNB cohort), spark module on other burners as paired-cohort service when matched-wear cycle aligns.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 6-9:</strong> Oven thermostat ($245-$385), oven igniter ($165-$265 — separate from surface burner igniters; the oven igniter is heavier-duty and runs through more cycles), gas valve assembly ($345-$525) on the gas-line side.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 8-12:</strong> Convection fan motor on RNB convection-equipped variants ($325-$485 — the convection fan is dedicated to the oven cavity), oven door hinge ($345-$525), infrared broiler element ($385-$580 — BlueStar's infrared broiler runs hotter than standard electric broilers and the element reflects that in spec and cost).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 12+:</strong> Door glass replacement ($385-$680), full door seal replacement, main control board on units with electronic ignition control ($345-$525 — simpler electronics than competitor luxury brands, lower replacement cost).</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The RCS rangetop service tree is mechanically identical to the RNB cooktop side — same burner architecture, same spark modules, same ceramic igniters. RCS just removes the oven cavity (the unit installs flush with the countertop and pairs with a separate wall oven for the cooking system). Service approach is the same. Platinum BSP variants run higher-spec brass valves, heavier construction, and occasionally distinct part numbers — diagnostic identifies the configuration from the model tag before parts are ordered.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 WALL OVENS, COOKTOPS, OTHER -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Wall ovens, cooktops, range hoods, infrared broilers</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Beyond the ranges — BSWO wall ovens, RCS rangetops, infrared broilers.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Outside ranges and rangetops, BlueStar covers wall ovens (BSWO standard and Platinum variants), gas cooktops, range hoods matching the range collection visuals, and the brand's signature infrared broiler technology. Newer refrigerator and dishwasher additions get lighter service volume in LA but are within scope.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Wall ovens (BSWO standard, Platinum variants)</h3>
        <p>BSWO30AGS and similar 30-inch single wall ovens, plus 36-inch and double-cavity configurations. Service: bake / broil element ($245-$385), oven temperature sensor ($185-$285), control board ($345-$525), convection fan motor ($325-$485), door hinge alignment. Platinum BSWO variants run higher-spec components but the service tree overlaps cleanly with standard BSWO.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Infrared broilers</h3>
        <p>BlueStar's infrared broiler is a distinguishing technology — element runs hotter and faster than standard electric broilers, produces restaurant-style broiling. Service items: broiler element ($385-$580 — heavier-duty than standard, reflects in parts cost), broiler igniter, thermostat. Failure pattern is mostly element-wear at year 8-12 on heavy-use households (BlueStar owners broil more than average).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Gas cooktops</h3>
        <p>Standalone gas cooktops with the same open-burner architecture as RNB ranges. Service is mechanically identical to the rangetop side of the range work — burner caps, rings, ceramic igniters, spark modules. Smaller footprint, same service tree.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Range hoods (matching collections)</h3>
        <p>Wall-mount, under-cabinet, and island range hoods designed to match each BlueStar range collection visually. Same color program — match the range panel finish. Service: blower motor ($385-$580), fan switch, light socket and bulb, damper.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Refrigerators &amp; dishwashers (newer additions)</h3>
        <p>BlueStar added refrigerators and dishwashers to round out the kitchen suite — newer to the lineup, lower LA service volume than ranges. Service trees follow the broader luxury-tier patterns for each category. We service them when they come up, parts through Prizer-Painter direct.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Open-burner vs sealed-burner — why it matters</h3>
        <p>Wolf, Thermador, Viking, Bertazzoni all use sealed burners (burner enclosed beneath gas-tight surface). BlueStar uses open burners (commercial-style, burner cap and ring exposed). Service implication: BlueStar diagnostics are faster, parts costs per zone are lower, repairs are more straightforward. Different design philosophy, different service economics.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

